column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

There were approximately 2060 export and 500 young cattle penned representing a decrease of 690 head week-on-week. The usual buying group was present and operating in a cheaper market in places. Quality was good with a large proportion of the yarding carrying plenty of finish. Trade cattle sold firm to 4c/kg easier. Grown steers and bullocks sold firm to slightly dearer. Manufacturing steers gave back 4c to 6c/kg. Heavy heifers eased 3c/kg. Cows eased 5c to 15c/kg. Heavy bulls gained 5c to 10c/kg. 

Vealers sold from 297c to 380c/kg. Yearling trade steers made between 330c and 375c/kg. Yearling heifers to the trade sold between 310c and 376c/kg. Grown steers made from 330c to 388c/kg. Bullocks sold from 348c to 396c/kg. 

Heavy Friesian manufacturing steers made between 250c and 325c with the crossbred portion between 300c and 374c/kg. Most light and medium weight cows sold between 200c and 272c/kg. Heavy weight cows made mostly from 234c to 302c/kg. Heavy bulls sold from 275c to 320c/kg. 

Market reporter: Brendan Fletcher.
